Further, XPS analysis was carried out to determine the surface chemical compositions of both C-dots and Ag/C-dots (Fig. 2
                           ). It is observed from Fig. 2(a), three different peaks of C-dots at 286 eV, 531 eV and 400.01 eV, ascribed to C1s, O1s and N1s confirms the existence of the carbon, oxygen and nitrogen compounds in the C-dots. The XPS survey spectrum of Ag/C-dots confirms the appearance of C, N, O and Ag elements on its surface (Fig. 3
                           (a)). The deconvolution spectra of C1s, O1s and N1s in both C-dots and Ag/C-dots exhibit similar functional groups on their surface. Deconvolution of the C1s spectrum shows the peaks at 284.1 eV, 285.7 eV, 287.1 eV and 289.6 eV which explain that the gelatin-derived C-dots are functionalized with CC, CN, CO, OC groups, respectively (Fig. 2(b)). While these same peaks appeared at a binding energy of 284.7 eV, 286.06 eV, 287.80 eV and 288.3 eV for Ag/C-dots (Fig. 3(b)) [38]. Three different deconvoluted peaks were fitted for both C-dots and Ag/C-dots as shown in Fig. 2(c) and Fig. 3(c). The binding energy of three different peaks at 398.1 eV (CNH), 399.4 eV (NH) and 400.5 eV (CN) were observed in the case of C-dots (Fig. 2(d). These peaks were also detected in Ag/C-dots with binding energies of 398.21 eV, 399.72 eV and 400.36 eV for CNH, NH and CN, respectively (Fig. 3(d)). In addition, O1s demonstrated binding energies of 531.1 eV and 531.36 eV for C-dots and Ag/C-dots, respectively, with oxygen atoms on their surface (Fig. 3(d)). Further, the Ag3d spectrum exhibits four peaks at binding energies of 367.75 (Ag (o)), 374.33(Ag (o)), 368.65 (Ag (I)) and 373.48 (Ag (I)) (Fig. 3(e)) [42].

The colorimetric sensor analysis of Ag/C-dots probe-based imidacloprid in real samples such as tap water and tomatoes was tested. A comparable recovery percentage was observed in both samples. The recovery percentage of tap water tomato samples was found to be 96.05 % and 95.5 %, respectively (Table 1
                           ). Further, Table 2
                            compares the analytical performances of the presented approach with other techniques for the detection of IMD; the LOD and linear range of the current approach are better. Further, colorimetric analyses have the advantage of being inexpensive and easy to use as compared to most previously mentioned procedures.
